node.text: What’s up guys, this morning my buddy @nowel.m went out for a photo shoot at Jones Lake for his first photo shoot ever as a photographer - in fact he bought this camera less than 12 hours before the shoot. // we share our initial tips for the newest beginners to photography. TIP ONE: keep your horizon line straight, TIP TWO: keep the top of your subjects head below the horizon line for great portraits and TIP THREE: use a darkened gradient filter from the bottom of frame to direct the viewers eye to the subject. Thanks for watching! Have a great day :)

node.text: People often ask me how I make my GIFs. Of course, with anything, there are 100 ways to do it, but I wanted to show you guys what works best for me. I've been using the new @fujifilm_northamerica X-Pro3 for a few months now and have really enjoyed using it, so I brought it out to the local lake with some friends to make a GIF and show you guys my exact process. From the shoot, to the edit, to posting on social media, this is how I make the GIFs you often see on my timeline. #fujifilmpartner #sponsored

node.text: I shot this set late last year in Northern BC with my 83 year old grandfather and one of his best friends Ron. Today; Ron is no longer with us and I spent the day with my grandfather helping him recover from a heart surgery. It’s particularly difficult at his age to make a full recovery, and its not a guarantee. Makes me even more thankful for this trip last year, and for this very unlikely set of photos. If you’ve got some older grandparents or parents, don’t be afraid of spending some real time with them. I spent six days in the northern BC wilderness with the old guys and it was actually some of the most fun I had all year. And next year, the same trip won’t even be possible, especially with Ron already gone. Such is life; what we have today, we are not guaranteed to have tomorrow, be that health, freedom, sanity, loved ones, or peace of mind and soul, so if you have something today, go ahead and make the most of it

node.text: From a magical morning earlier this summer. *sound up* // the previous day I had gotten out of the mountains exhausted and passed out at 5pm at some campground up a dirt road. After twelve or so hours I woke up ten mins up the road from this spot, found it on a map and drove straight there. Was very happy to find a deer already chilling in the lake eating breakfast right at sunrise

node.text: Been wanting this aerial shot of the entirety of Widgeon Lake for quite some time and the story behind how it came to life is actually pretty good. @austonianb and I were doing this project last winter that came with a budget for up to $1500 of transportation. Typically something like that would be used for gas, commercial air travel, or ferries for example. But since travel was basically shut down for the most part, we used a helicopter to “transport” us to the mountains and shot the project out there. Booking the flight was a risk but they ended up being totally on board with it and happily reimbursed all the costs. Gotta pay to get into a solid location after all. // On the way back I asked the pilot to leave the shoot by exiting “in two large ascending circles.” And I shot this with my 6 year old Canon 6D since my main body was occupied by Austin shooting for the actual video. #fieldstories

node.text: Chilliwack Lake and the river valley from the summit of Flora Peak last summer. A solid 12 hour sunset to sunrise solo mission. Saw a bear in the first 1km of hiking but felt safe finishing because it’s response to seeing me was getting as far away from me as possible. Just another day in the BC backcountry

node.text: This right here is why I keep the long lens on me. Shot at 200mm at 6.7k with a 2x digital crop so effectively 400mm. I remember early on in my outdoor recreation career thinking elk were just kinda chill and walking up to a bull at a golf course, and it squared me up and bluffed charged me 😂 a 700+ pound animal with antlers as wide as a car bumper. Learn a lesson from me and get close to elk via telephoto lens, quite helpful
